id entry; that said tract is not settled\nupon and cultivated as required by law;\nand has never established his actual resi\ndence nor made any improvements on the\nland since he made the homestead entry\nand that said alleged absence from the\nsaid land was not due to his employment\nin the Army, Navy or Marine Corps of\nthe United States as a private soldier,\nofficer, seaman or marine during the war\nwith Spain or during any other war in\nwhich the United States may be engaged.\"\nSaid parties are hereby notified to appear,\nrespond and oiler evidence touching said\nallegation at 10 o'clock a. m. on March\n13,11908, before N.V. Ciallegos, U.S. Court\nCommissioner, at his office in Tucumeari,\nNew Mexico (and that final hearing will be\nheld at 10 o'clock a. in. on March jo, 1908,\nbefore the Kogister and receiver at the\nUnited States Land Office in Clayton,\nNew Mexico,\nThe contestant having in proper affida\nvit, filed lanuary 8, 1908, set forth facts\nwhich show that after due diligence per\nsonal service of this notice can not bo\nmade, it is hereby ordered and directed\nthat such notice be given by due and pro\nper publication. t\nKdwaki) W. KoX, Register\nCONTEST NOTICE.\nDepartment of the Interior, United\nStates Land Office, Clayton New Mexico.\nJanuary 13, 1908.\nA sufficient contest affidavit having been\nfiled in this office by Ephriam W. Sparks,\ncontestant against Homestead Entry No.\n160G3 made March 12, 1907 for 02 sw.f and\nwa se.j Sec 31, Twp 7n, Range 35c by\nChester Hamilton, contestee, in which\nit is alleged under date of September\n13, 1907, that the said Chester Hamilton\nhas wholly abandoned said tracf.that he has\nchanged his residence therefrom for more\nthan six months next prior to the date of\nsaid affidavit; that he has not settled upon\nand cultivated said tract as required by\nlaw; and that said alleged absence was\nnot due to his employment in the armv,\nnavy or marine corps of the United States\nas a private soldier, officer, seaman or\nmarine during the war with Spain or dur\ning any other war in which the United\nStates may be engaged.\nSaid parties are hereby notified to ap\npear, respond and offer evidence touching\nsaid allegation at ten o'clock a. in. on Feb\nruary 1 90S before A. E. Curran, U. S.\nCommissioner at his oflice in Ulovis,\nNew Mexico, and that final hearing\nwill be held at ten o'clock a. m. on March\n4, kjoS before the Register and Receiv\ner at the United States Land Office in\nClayton, New Mexico.\nThe said contestant having, in a proper\naffidavit filed kjo. set forth\nfacts which show that after due diligence\npersonal service of this notice can not be\nmade, it is hereby ordered and directed\nthat such notice be given by due and proper\npublication.\nEdward W. Fox, Register.\nS\nMi\n4? 3 a,\nFURNISHED ROOM\nCARDS\nr4\nMi\n0\nill\nHi nr r a'\nmu 1 ucumcan rnnung ko,\nt e fr fr e e-1 f- fr e f\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nAn Interview With Max B.\nGoldenberg, One of Our\nMost Substantial Bus\niness Men\nBUSINESS PROSPERING\nAND BANKS SOLID\nThe reporter had an interview\nwith Max Goldenberg, one of our\nmost substantial business men, on\nthe outlook for business this spring,\nwhich is given in part, following:\nMr. Goldenberg keeps well in\nformed on local affairs and is per\nhaps better acquainted with con\nditions than any other merchant in\ntown, and as a successful and con\nservative business man his opti\nmistic views are to be considered\nencouraging.\nHe says: ''From letters receiv\ned from various points of the Ter\nritory, especially from the Pecos\nValley, from people that have\nformerly resided at Tucumeari, it\nappears that the business situation\nat Tucumeari is in better shape\nthan at any of the towns in Eastern\nNew Mexico.\nThe receipts of our business\nhouses have not fallen off in com\nparison with sales made at the\nsame time last year; on the con\ntrary good increase have been\nmade.\nThe real estate situation is in a\nvery good condition; six lots were\nsold recently in the Barnes\nRankin Addition, at $150 for in\nside lots and $2.00 for corners;\ntwo lots in the Daub First Addi\ntion at $200 each, inside lots; one\nlot in the original townsite at $200;\nand several lots have been sold in\nthe Aber Addition. All of these\nprices are considered as good as\nreceived before the financial flurry\nstarted in. There is a good deal\nof inquiry at present for business\nproperty, and I understand that\n$5000 has been offered for two lots\non Main Street, and several farms\nhave changed hands in the last\nfew days, sold by local real estate\ndealers.\nThe deposits of our banks have\nincreased since January 1st, 1908,\nand we can feel proud that our\nlocal banks rue in better condition\nthan any banks in the Territory.\"\nYasscen has moved his jewelry\ninto the Famous Store where it\nwill stay until new quarters are\nprovided in the Trust Building\nCompany block.\nWhen you buy an outfit of An\nderson he cuts and fits your pipe\nwithout any cost to 14-tf\ni","height":"29760","width":"20584"}}
